            <div class="ExistArti p-2">
                <h2 class="EArtiTitle">
                    Why is it created?
                </h2>
                <p class="existCon">It's important to remember that there can be a variety of reasons and causes false information spreads online.</p>
                <br/>
                <h4 class="existSub">
                    Unintentional Fake News
                </h4>
                <p class="existCon">
                    Due to the recent concern over growing amounts of misinformation generated online, academics at Massachusetts Institute of Technology have been researching how unintentional mis-information can be spread so easily online.  They found that around 50% of active internet users have spread misinformation at some point- usually because their attention is focused on something else.
                <br/>
                    People generally share content that creates some form of emotional response.  Often with memes, this could be because they find the content funny.  If they find a joke that they don't find funny, there's not much chance they'd pass it on.  Other emotions lead to people sharing online content also- it could be content they really agree with, or something that makes them angry among many others.
                <br/>
                    The issue is when people see and repost content online, it can become like a game of Telephone where the message gets changed over time.   As stories become more and more factually inaccurate, they tend to be spread and shared even more as often these factual inaccuracies create a stronger emotion.  For example, if someone sees a meme and changes it to make it even more funny, this funnier version is more likely to be spread by the next person.   After several people have changed the meme, it may end up being completely different from the original joke - just like the game of Telephone.
                <br/>
                    Unfortunately, when this comes to political ideas and beliefs, the same ideas cause people to unintentionally create and share information.  When they see a story online that really aligns with their beliefs, they're much more likely to share it.  The MIT study even showed that when sharing content online, people are more focused on whether it aligns with their beliefs over whether the content is factually accurate.  However, each time the story is shared, the facts changed tend to make the story align even more with the political viewpoint.
                <br/>
                    As a result of this, no one intentionally changed the story.  However over time the story became Fake News as crucial details were changed.  The following video explains this issue further.
                <br/>
                    <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rE3j_RHkqJc">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rE3j_RHkqJc</a>
                    <br/>
                    <div align=center>
                    <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/rE3j_RHkqJc"  title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>
                    </div>
                    <br/>
                </p>
                <p class="existCon">
