                <h4 class="existSub">Intentional False Information</h4>
                <br/>
                <p class="existCon">
                    Generally intentional false information can be designed for the following reasons:
                    <br/>
                    <br />
                     - To provoke an individual or a group
                    <br />
                     - To profit
                    <br />
                     - To damage an individual or organisation's reputation
                    <br />
                     - As political influence
                    <br />
                     - As Satire
                    <br />
                    <br />
                    Intentional false information is especially dangerous, as it can be carefully designed in a way that even if people eventually realise it's false information, their behaviour still gets changed enough to cause the desired effect.  A famous example of this was the link between the MMR vaccine and autism.  In 1998, researchers falsified a research paper linking the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine to behavioural regression and pervasive development disorder in children.  While this fake news was almost immediately debunked by multiple organisations and universities, to this day people hold scepticism towards certain vaccines with their link to autism [1].
                    <br />
                    In this case, the false information was designed as a way for a particular company to profit and to damage another organisations reputation.  However, false information has been created recently to push forward certain ideologies or political ideas.
                    <br/>
                    Source:
                    <br/>
                    <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3136032/">
                        [1] https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3136032/
                    </a>
                </p>
                <h4 class="existSub">Biased Information</h4>
                <br/>
                <p class="existCon">
                    Biased information can be another form of fake news. While biased news falls mostly into the category of malformation biased information can also be presented where the information is entirely factual, however it encourages the readers to form a particular political opinion.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>Malinformation - Information which may be true or partially true, but told in a way to cause the readers to draw incorrect conclusions.
                    </em>
                    <br />
                    <br />
                    Biased information could be both intentional or unintentional.  And neither is necessarily wrong to do.
                </p>
                <br/>
                <p class="existSub1">Loaded Words</p>
                <p class="existCon">This is wording that attempts to influence an audience by trying to create an emotional reaction.</p>
                <p class="existSub1"> Omitting Certain Information</p>
                <p class="existCon">This occurs when information is omitted to prevent damage to the authors political cause.</p>
                <p class="existSub1"> Story Selection</p>
                <p class="existCon">
                    This typically occurs on news websites, although it can also occur in social media.  This is where the publisher chooses to only post a story or information if it supports their political cause.  If a story comes up that hurts their cause, they would not publish anything and pretend it doesn't exist.  When reading information from biased media using this technique, it gives the illusion that everyone supports these same beliefs and all the world events currently happening also support this view.
                <br/>
                <br/>
                Any of these three things doesn't necessarily make the story false information.  However, each of them can cause the reader to draw specific conclusions.  These conclusions the reader draws is not necessarily factual.
                </p>
